item.p:
Whether or not the &app_pick_peer;
application callback can modify the application state.
Defaults to false.

item.pre:
eval([{M,F,A} | T]) ->
    apply(M, F, T ++ A);
eval([[F|A] | T]) ->
    eval([F | T ++ A]);
eval([F|A]) ->
    apply(F, A);
eval(F) ->
    eval([F]).

item.p:
Applying an &eval;
E to an argument list A
is meant in the sense of eval([E|A]).

item.pre:
Result = ResultCode | {capabilities_cb, CB, ResultCode|discard}
Caps = #diameter_caps{}
Pkt  = #diameter_packet{}
ResultCode = integer()
CB = &eval;

Result = ResultCode | atom() | {capabilities_cb, CB, ResultCode|discard}
Caps = #diameter_caps{}
Pkt  = #diameter_packet{}
ResultCode = integer()

Ref = &transport_ref;
PeerRef = &app_peer_ref;
From, To = initial | okay | suspect | down | reopen
Config = {connect|listen, [transport_opt()]}

desc.p:
If there are no suitable peers, or if
&app_pick_peer;
rejects them by returning false, then {error,no_connection}
is returned.
Otherwise &app_pick_peer; is followed by a
&app_prepare_request; callback, the message is encoded and then sent.

item.p:
If the initial encode of the outgoing request
fails, then the request process fails and {error,encode}
is returned.
